WEBVTT

00:00.898 --> 00:07.467
Well, I mean, I think by the time we get here next week, we will have been Christmas-ified here in the auditorium.

00:07.808 --> 00:11.553
Give me a show of hands if you've already got your Christmas decorations up.

00:12.194 --> 00:12.935
Oh, I love that.

00:13.155 --> 00:13.676
Do you know what?

00:13.696 --> 00:14.958
We were so tempted.

00:14.978 --> 00:21.247
The only reason we haven't is that our lounge is full of laundry at the moment, and it just doesn't offset the right vibe.

00:22.048 --> 00:24.231
But it's going to happen probably tomorrow.

00:24.291 --> 00:28.417
And if you're doing it this week, give me a show of hands, not yet, but you're about to.

00:28.597 --> 00:29.138
Yes.

00:29.218 --> 00:34.501
the traditionalists who have to wait until the beginning of Advent, officially, first of December.

00:35.224 --> 00:39.282
Okay, well, this morning we're going to be doing things a little bit differently.

00:39.394 --> 00:47.703
About two and a half years ago now, I interviewed our then relatively new community pastor, Eddie Lawless.

00:48.344 --> 00:51.026
And since then, so much has happened.

00:51.107 --> 00:58.635
And we really wanted to bring us as a church into the loop of what's taking place beyond the four walls of Skylark.

00:58.675 --> 01:04.121
Now, obviously, in and through each one of us, we are an extension of the church wherever we go.

01:04.141 --> 01:09.266
So it's not necessarily all about the centralised thing, but

01:10.114 --> 01:28.092
As we step into our centenary year in January, 100 years since the inception of this church, I want to remind us that Skylark Church began as Bethel Church and actually it was just one woman who saw a need on her doorstep.

01:28.813 --> 01:37.362
She saw a group of children playing and the story goes that her heart was moved with compassion because she saw these kids playing

01:37.474 --> 01:43.882
The Lord just began to whisper to her that they were like sheep without a shepherd, and she was moved by that.

01:44.503 --> 01:50.510
And the Holy Spirit prompted her to take action just to do something about that need that she saw.

01:50.570 --> 01:57.739
And she invited those kids into her home, and a little Sunday school was born.

01:58.240 --> 02:03.526
And then she began to invite parents and carers and families, and it just began to grow.

02:03.546 --> 02:06.770
And that's part of our DNA.

02:07.554 --> 02:15.067
seeing need on our doorstep and not turning a blind eye, but actually rolling our past leaves and getting stuck in.

02:15.548 --> 02:20.577
We are a church that is called to local mission and to translocal mission.

02:21.298 --> 02:26.006
And a couple of years ago, we shared with you as a church a vision that we had had.

02:26.046 --> 02:27.549
Well, actually, it happened in real life.

02:27.569 --> 02:28.510
It wasn't even a vision.

02:28.631 --> 02:32.978
We saw a tractor going past as we were praying in France.

02:33.442 --> 02:40.830
And we sense that the Lord was talking to us about harvest and that we were coming into a season of harvest as a church.

02:41.390 --> 02:57.106
And I want to tell you in a moment, you're going to hear stories of just a snapshot of some of the incredible things that God is doing through Skylark Church and through other churches in Champsford to see his kingdom come and that harvest is happening.

02:58.628 --> 03:00.850
In Isaiah 61, it says this.

03:02.050 --> 03:09.899
The spirit of the sovereign Lord is upon me, for the Lord has anointed me to bring good news to the poor.

03:10.800 --> 03:19.850
He has sent me to comfort the brokenhearted and to proclaim that captives will be released and prisoners will be freed.

03:20.571 --> 03:30.962
He has sent me to tell those who mourn that the time of the Lord's favor has come and with it the day of God's anger against their enemies.

03:31.938 --> 03:33.940
to all who mourn in Israel.

03:34.521 --> 03:45.152
He will give a crown of beauty for ashes, a joyous blessing instead of mourning, festive praise instead of despair, what an exchange.

03:46.273 --> 03:53.701
In their righteousness, they will be like great oaks that the Lord has planted for his own glory.

03:54.502 --> 03:59.828
They will rebuild the ancient ruins repairing cities destroyed long ago.

03:59.888 --> 04:01.810
They will revive them.

04:02.018 --> 04:05.583
though they have been deserted for many generations.

04:06.644 --> 04:14.834
You know, our community is just one of the ways in which we here as a church outwork that mandate in Isaiah 61.

04:15.235 --> 04:20.782
And so I'd love to welcome up Eddie Lawless, and we're going to have a little conversation about what's happening.

04:21.242 --> 04:22.183
Come on up, Eddie.

04:25.247 --> 04:25.548
Hello.

04:28.411 --> 04:30.514
Eddie, we have vision statements on our wall.

04:30.690 --> 04:41.225
We see a church offering shelter to the marginalized, rest to the weary, justice to the oppressed, and restoration to the broken.

04:41.245 --> 04:49.817
And we also have one that says, we see a church embracing, enriching, and impacting the local community.

04:49.837 --> 04:52.420
Those are powerful statements of vision, aren't they?

04:52.741 --> 04:58.849
And it's two and a half years since we lasted this, time has flown, flies when you're having fun.

04:58.869 --> 04:59.570
Are you having fun?

04:59.842 --> 05:01.906
Yeah, that's good to hear.

05:03.410 --> 05:06.096
So much has happened and it's hard to really know where to start.

05:06.196 --> 05:08.681
But I'd like to start with you to begin with.

05:09.483 --> 05:14.253
Can you share the why behind the what we do?

05:14.293 --> 05:20.146
Because it's really easy for us to delve straight into activity and to tell everybody what we're doing.

05:20.226 --> 05:22.629
But I'd like to start with the heartbeat.

05:22.930 --> 05:27.697
What is that thing that gets you out of bed in the morning that you're most passionate about seeing?

05:27.877 --> 05:29.779
And why are we doing this stuff?

05:30.901 --> 05:32.063
OK, so the why?

05:32.103 --> 05:33.925
Sorry, I'm just getting comfortable.

05:34.466 --> 05:36.529
If you know me well, you know, I don't sit normally ever.

05:37.030 --> 05:39.073
And so the why is people.

05:39.573 --> 05:42.898
And anyone who knows me well will know that people are both

05:43.362 --> 05:47.205
the most frustrating part of my job, but also the thing that gets me out of bed.

05:47.325 --> 05:49.507
Like, I just fascinated by people.

05:49.527 --> 05:51.729
I love hearing their stories.

05:52.190 --> 05:55.613
I love getting alongside people and building relationships with people.

05:56.333 --> 05:58.075
So the people are the why.

05:58.996 --> 06:01.598
Like, I love every single person in this room.

06:01.698 --> 06:03.079
I love our church family.

06:03.499 --> 06:09.365
But just by very nature of you being here, you're already on a journey with Jesus, even if it's like the very beginning.

06:09.765 --> 06:13.348
Maybe your 10 decades deep, well, maybe not 10, but many decades

06:13.328 --> 06:19.638
deep or maybe it's your first time in church but you've already made that step to find out more about who Jesus is.

06:20.499 --> 06:34.962
What I get to do in my role as community pastor is go out there and meet with people who have not yet experienced anything to do with Jesus and I get to do that in sometimes really overt ways with the alpha course and stuff like that where it's

06:35.138 --> 06:58.307
The sole purpose is to talk to them about Jesus, but it also gets to it in really subtle ways, where I can just build relationships with people, and Jesus isn't necessarily the focus point in terms of what we're there for, but it just brings Jesus in in a really gentle, subtle way through relationship building and just journeying with people.

06:58.968 --> 07:03.794
And so that's the why, and I'm just super passionate about

07:04.418 --> 07:31.922
people particularly those on the margins and those that don't necessarily fit in our society in the way that a lot of us do and I'm probably passionate about that because I found myself on those fringes in the past and in my life and various points so I recognize how it feels to feel like you don't belong or that you don't fit or this isn't for you or you're not good enough and so that's kind of the driving force and

07:32.482 --> 07:40.694
The point for me is to bring light into the darkness and you can't bring light into the darkness unless you're prepared to go into the dark.

07:41.175 --> 07:44.800
And that's something that God spoke really clearly when I took this role on.

07:44.861 --> 07:47.905
It's like we're not just going to do the same as we've always done.

07:47.985 --> 07:51.090
We're not going to just tread that path that's already been trodden.

07:51.450 --> 08:01.906
We're going to go into the rough terrain and we're going to find ourselves in places that maybe we would prefer not to be because that's where it's darkest and that's where my light is needed the most.

08:02.402 --> 08:02.983
Beautiful.

08:03.403 --> 08:05.727
And at Advent, what a great depiction as well.

08:06.748 --> 08:14.439
We think about light in the darkness, Jesus being the light of the world, but then that commission is for us also to be the light of the world.

08:14.460 --> 08:27.218
Now, these verses in Isaiah that I read out at the start of this interview, they touch on good news for the poor, they touch on captives being set free, binding up the brokenhearted,

08:27.522 --> 08:49.756
and so much more this idea of rebuilding ruins, this rebuilding those deserted places and spaces and we can look around the city of Chelmsford and surrounding areas from which many of us come in from here at Skylark Church and just see so many deserted places in our communities right now.

08:49.797 --> 08:53.362
I know that

08:54.050 --> 08:58.427
this work has significantly expanded in the last couple of years.

08:58.527 --> 09:03.346
So I'd love it if you could just give us an overview on Vision Sunday.

09:03.490 --> 09:08.535
Pete always reels off so much that's happening both in the church, beyond the church.

09:08.736 --> 09:18.006
And what you hear are maybe two sentences, but behind each of those two sentences, there's probably a day's worth of conversation that we could have.

09:18.086 --> 09:28.677
So for us, this is a way of kind of preparing before January for us as a church to understand that behind those headlines, there are so many lives being impacted.

09:28.737 --> 09:33.202
So tell us, what are some of the key community activities

09:33.314 --> 09:41.696
projects long-term vision that we are sowing into and then we're going to zoom in much more closely on some specifics.

09:41.776 --> 09:48.093
We have probably, well, it started as six main areas that we invest into in our community.

09:48.113 --> 09:50.098
It's now seven because, you know,

09:50.274 --> 09:51.776
God loves the number seven.

09:51.796 --> 09:52.217
I think that's okay.

09:52.237 --> 09:53.719
There is something about seven, isn't there?

09:54.360 --> 09:56.243
So firstly, let's start with poverty.

09:56.384 --> 10:01.972
So obviously there is a deep need in our country at the moment to alleviate poverty.

10:02.373 --> 10:04.576
And we do that in a very practical way, which is beautiful.

10:04.616 --> 10:07.741
And it's a way that a lot of our volunteers can get involved with.

10:08.242 --> 10:10.966
And so we deliver hampers to the local community.

10:11.126 --> 10:18.578
And we're given those names by local schools and people within our congregation, the council, and we deliver those

10:18.690 --> 10:29.138
hampers once a month and then an extra one at Christmas with nice treats and just ways to make them feel loved and seen and we also cook meals well I say we

10:29.250 --> 10:30.912
you wouldn't want it if I'd cooked it.

10:31.432 --> 10:48.231
The wonderful Leslie Kemp and the team, I think Paul and Kimmy are amongst those people, they come and they cook every month like hundreds of meals that then get distributed out with our hampers and they just remain in our freezer as well for people within the church that may need meals at any point.

10:48.271 --> 10:57.682
So they just do such an amazing job and it's so nice for people to receive a home-cooked meal, not just bog-standard bits that they have to do something with.

10:57.826 --> 11:19.090
We have been very blessed to have a bursary fund that we're able to access for people within the community and that looks like, we'll get a phone call from the council for example, this is one thing that's happened saying there's a young woman with twins moving into the area, she has absolutely nothing.

11:19.234 --> 11:30.705
how can you help and we can go, oh, we can get her a bed, we can get her some bedding, we can get her toys for the kids, we can do, do, do, do, do, and just be able to do it because that money is sat there ready for situations just like that.

11:31.206 --> 11:31.486
Wow.

11:31.827 --> 11:32.828
Yeah, it's cool.

11:32.848 --> 11:33.828
It's awesome, isn't it?

11:33.849 --> 11:34.729
It's really cool.

11:35.570 --> 11:39.674
When I get to do stuff like that, it's like, I love my job, this is so cool.

11:40.395 --> 11:42.697
But we do it in various different ways.

11:42.777 --> 11:47.442
We've given freezers, we've given washing machines, and we've had

11:48.770 --> 11:51.916
calls just saying, is there any chance that you give some vouchers to this lady?

11:51.936 --> 11:58.949
She's got no food at all, and she can't relate with people very well, so would it be possible to just bring a voucher and we're able to do that.

11:58.969 --> 11:59.831
So that's poverty.

12:01.133 --> 12:04.960
And prison, and we're going to delve into this a bit more, but I'll give you the highlights.

12:05.461 --> 12:12.274
So we have been working in the prison now for about a year and a half, and we run Sunday services, so basically we do this.

12:12.386 --> 12:14.557
in there every couple of months.

12:14.738 --> 12:16.588
Even on Christmas Day, the team went in last year.

12:16.628 --> 12:19.242
Christmas Day, we went in last year, which was awesome.

12:19.885 --> 12:20.850
Really cool.

12:22.434 --> 12:26.381
We do a mental health and wellbeing course in there that we run on a Monday night.

12:27.203 --> 12:31.952
We have launched the first ever Messy Church in prison, which is very cool.

12:31.972 --> 12:32.873
So we've done two of those.

12:33.174 --> 12:34.757
We do one every holidays.

12:35.438 --> 12:36.901
So that's been really exciting.

12:37.301 --> 12:44.435
We are helping and taking over the running of Alpha in the prison in the New Year, and we offer press support in there as well.

12:44.655 --> 12:46.258
So the prison is growing.

12:46.402 --> 12:47.284
exponentially.

12:47.605 --> 12:48.668
It's very, very cool.

12:49.069 --> 12:50.011
So exciting.

12:50.031 --> 12:50.412
Yes.

12:50.432 --> 12:51.294
So exciting.

12:51.314 --> 12:52.377
Modern day slavery.

12:53.199 --> 12:59.635
We sit on various different groups within the cast thing.

12:59.655 --> 13:02.642
I don't know what the word is, but cast stands.

13:02.946 --> 13:04.508
chance with against slavery partnership.

13:04.989 --> 13:14.802
So it's a multi-organizational link with the council and the police that looks at how we can address modern day slavery in our city and how we can impact.

13:15.383 --> 13:26.898
So we sit on various boards, the steering board, the disruption group and survival care, which we're working quite closely with at the moment to see how we can support those who have been

13:26.946 --> 13:30.458
freed from that environment and now are in survival mode.

13:31.100 --> 13:33.448
So it's a very exciting part of my job.

13:33.689 --> 13:37.682
There was one time where I went on a disruption thing.

13:38.274 --> 13:50.039
whatever they call it, and I was driving around in a police car and just happened to see somebody from the church at a petrol station and got out of the car and he was like, all right Eddy, okay, what are you doing?

13:50.059 --> 13:57.575
I was like, I can't say, it's really awkward, but yeah, definitely see a lot of interesting things working in that area.

13:57.735 --> 13:59.218
So if that was you now you know.

13:59.490 --> 14:04.177
And restored, which is our domestic abuse arm.

14:05.359 --> 14:08.444
We support victims and survivors of domestic abuse.

14:09.145 --> 14:10.527
That looks like going to court.

14:10.787 --> 14:25.490
It looks like one-to-one or two-to-one interactions, like little WhatsApp groups supporting one another, safe spaces for people to come and use our building as a place where they can make phone calls or use the internet.

14:25.794 --> 14:43.608
We also support other churches in the area with that and because we were the beacon church, like the first beacon church and I'm the beacon lead, I get to kind of just go, right, this is what we've experienced and this is how it looks like for us and kind of support them on their journey as well.

14:43.628 --> 14:44.690
So that's really cool.

14:45.570 --> 14:46.331
Schools work.

14:46.632 --> 14:49.476
So we work in secondary schools and we work in Shumpswood College.

14:50.138 --> 15:01.236
In secondary schools we run a course called Flourish which is for girls and we run that in five different schools at the moment with a brilliant team and we're going to talk more about that so I won't go too much about that.

15:01.637 --> 15:09.810
But we're also writing or almost finished writing with wonderful Kate Gower now our youth pastor and a boys course as well which is going to be

15:10.018 --> 15:14.843
launching in the New Year and piloting to see if we can impact some of the boys in our schools as well.

15:15.143 --> 15:15.884
So so needed.

15:16.104 --> 15:16.825
So needed.

15:17.425 --> 15:24.132
And I also go into the Chancellor's College and offer counseling for particularly children who've been bereaved.

15:24.152 --> 15:35.723
And there's been a really high number of suicides, not just pupils, but pupils' parents who have remained really, really stuck in that grief.

15:35.863 --> 15:39.186
So I go in and offer some counseling to them as well.

15:39.490 --> 16:06.162
and mental health that leads on to you nicely and we offer one-to-one support here and we have a brilliant counseling team and and we have Kinsugi hope which is a emotional well-being group and we run that here as well and so we're just trying to continue to break down the stigma related to mental health and make sure people realise that it's okay to admit that you're not doing okay and this is a safe place in order to see that

16:06.242 --> 16:14.293
And finally, loneliness and isolation, we really recognise that that is an epidemic in our country and we're just trying to meet some of the needs there.

16:14.313 --> 16:20.201
So we have Leanne, who runs Belong on a Monday, which is just this beautiful intergenerational group.

16:20.561 --> 16:21.382
Isn't it gorgeous?

16:22.083 --> 16:22.744
Just stunning.

16:23.165 --> 16:27.250
I remember on Christmas Day, I think it was Christmas Day last year, the

16:27.650 --> 16:38.365
Most senior member of that group had a phone call from one of the youngest because she just couldn't possibly imagine not saying happy Christmas to this guy, which is just gorgeous.

16:38.445 --> 16:43.913
So those relationships have been built and they transcend what happened here on a Monday.

16:44.213 --> 16:51.163
We're also looking at befriending services and getting involved with care homes and things like that as well in order to meet the need of isolation.

16:51.424 --> 16:52.185
So that's the seven.

16:52.485 --> 16:53.206
Well, not much then.

16:55.029 --> 16:55.890
Wow.

16:56.898 --> 17:10.172
I'd like to zoom in now because that's just broad brushstrokes, but there's stories, there's real lives, there's incredible team members, there's so much work that goes and prayer that goes into each of these areas.

17:10.192 --> 17:21.284
And I'd like us to focus on prison because when Pete and I joined the church back in 2001 now, one of the first areas that we ever served in was prison alpha.

17:21.885 --> 17:26.770
And I remember we used to go in, didn't we, quite regularly with a team

17:26.914 --> 17:34.886
But then I can't remember exactly when, maybe several years later, our access into the prison just got the door kind of shut.

17:35.607 --> 17:39.713
And when you stepped into your role, that door was still very much shut, wasn't it?

17:39.773 --> 17:53.714
But it's been on our heart and something that we've been collectively praying for and longing for for some time to really be able to get into the prison and to bring hope to those inmates in champs for as long as they're with us.

17:54.114 --> 18:02.948
Well, it would be lovely for you to tell us a bit about Champs for Prison anyway because it's quite unique in the way it functions in terms of how long inmates are there for.

18:03.309 --> 18:13.085
So tell us a little bit about the journey that led up to that open door and some of the stories that you are able to share about how we've seen God at work.

18:13.766 --> 18:21.298
Yeah, it's an exciting story and I could bore you to death on this so I will try not to get too excited and too much.

18:21.442 --> 18:27.650
As you said, people have been praying for years for us, like, really diligently praying.

18:28.311 --> 18:29.473
And it just hasn't happened.

18:29.593 --> 18:34.019
And when I first took on this role, honestly, it wasn't really on my horizon.

18:34.339 --> 18:37.664
Like, I knew we wanted to be in, but I wasn't really sure where to start.

18:38.625 --> 18:40.828
And then, you know, it all happened.

18:40.888 --> 18:47.637
But rollback nearly nine years ago when we first joined this church was a nine or 10 years ago.

18:47.657 --> 18:48.498
Ten, I think.

18:48.706 --> 18:58.000
10 years ago when we joined this church and our first Sunday, Nikki saw us sat right over there and came over to us and was like, I've got a word for UT.

18:58.060 --> 19:00.284
Now, I come from a church where that's not normal.

19:00.925 --> 19:03.509
So I was a bit like, okay, weird.

19:03.789 --> 19:04.971
I came brilliant.

19:04.991 --> 19:12.402
So she, she spoke to us and she was like, I've just got this real sense that you are going to have keys.

19:12.514 --> 19:37.714
like lots of keys and they're really ornate and there's loads of them and they all open different doors and you're just going to be collecting them but at some point in the future you're going to be holding these keys and then Champs of Prison happened and now I hold these keys which is just, it blows my mind how God can use something that was prophesied in ten years ago and now we're seeing it

19:38.210 --> 19:46.258
come into fruition and I guess as an encouragement, if something was spoken over to you over you a long time ago and you're like, well, I haven't seen it yet, God, what are you doing?

19:46.402 --> 19:51.069
just keep believing for it because it will come, what he promises he fulfills.

19:51.490 --> 19:55.477
And so now I hold these keys which is, you know, it blows my mind, it's actually bonkers.

19:55.837 --> 20:00.044
And actually other people on my team now hold keys as well and they think it's bonkers too.

20:00.945 --> 20:09.198
But we have access and we literally have those doors flinging wide open for us and it's been relatively easy which just shows it must be God.

20:09.559 --> 20:13.025
God's fingerprints have been all over it because it's absolutely nothing I do.

20:13.065 --> 20:13.906
In fact,

20:13.986 --> 20:17.892
I didn't even think to say, can I come and work in the prison?

20:17.912 --> 20:21.017
I was going in, going, oh, how can we support you?

20:21.077 --> 20:21.998
How can we pray for you?

20:22.298 --> 20:24.642
How can we offer you some supervision back at our church?

20:24.722 --> 20:26.345
And she was like, I think, actually.

20:26.725 --> 20:27.707
You need to come in here.

20:27.787 --> 20:29.810
So, yeah, it's God.

20:30.030 --> 20:31.052
It's entirely God.

20:31.673 --> 20:38.002
Now I actually give one day of my week to the prison, spread over two afternoons and evenings.

20:38.466 --> 20:42.251
And like I said, we do Sunday services, which are just beautiful.

20:42.951 --> 20:50.821
We run Kinsugi in there, which is the wellbeing and mental health group that's on a Monday night with a team of people who are insanely good at what they do.

20:50.841 --> 21:02.415
And we get to meet with usually around 12 guys at any one time, who can come and be honest and open and vulnerable, which I did not expect in a prison.

21:02.715 --> 21:06.200
I did not expect people to be able to be vulnerable with each other, let alone ours.

21:06.340 --> 21:08.242
I thought they were going to come with this.

21:08.450 --> 21:09.852
What do you know about anything?

21:09.892 --> 21:11.233
Like, why would I talk to you?

21:11.974 --> 21:26.810
But they've been really vulnerable and we've had tears, we've had joyous moments, we've celebrated with them, we've commiserated with them, we've been on the ground in their just absolute despair.

21:27.551 --> 21:29.393
And it's such a beautiful privilege.

21:30.074 --> 21:33.778
And now we run alpha.

21:33.986 --> 21:37.210
I think it was probably about three or four weeks ago.

21:37.230 --> 21:45.421
Seven of the guys at Alpha gave their life to Jesus, which was just like, what?

21:45.461 --> 21:46.663
It was so cool.

21:47.263 --> 21:58.578
So getting to witness what Jesus is doing in the lives of these people, despite their circumstances, despite the cells, despite the keys, despite the closed doors,

21:58.978 --> 22:01.261
God is not restricted by any of that.

22:01.281 --> 22:04.724
And he is transforming lives in that place, which is so exciting.

22:05.365 --> 22:06.687
And a couple of stories.

22:07.047 --> 22:13.774
So there was one guy who comes every Sunday and he loves a certain song.

22:14.415 --> 22:19.341
And I was walking through the prison on a day that wasn't a Sunday to a different event that I'd been invited to speak at.

22:19.661 --> 22:27.269
And all I heard from one of the cells as I was walking across the ground, so I was, open the eyes of my heart, Lord.

22:27.470 --> 22:27.890
And I was like,

22:28.674 --> 22:30.116
I know exactly who that is.

22:30.136 --> 22:31.198
I know exactly.

22:31.238 --> 22:32.561
And he did it to get my attention.

22:32.621 --> 22:35.445
He knew I'd knew who he was if he sang that song.

22:35.506 --> 22:37.208
So later on in the day, I went and found him.

22:37.248 --> 22:38.410
I was like, that was you, wasn't it?

22:38.931 --> 22:40.554
And he's like, yeah, yeah, that was me.

22:40.614 --> 22:42.517
And I was like, right, OK, we're in next Sunday.

22:42.537 --> 22:44.140
You're going to sing it with me on Sunday.

22:44.701 --> 22:47.666
And from there, we have seen

22:47.810 --> 23:15.218
spontaneous worship break out at the end of a service on a Sunday which is just beautiful and that is thanks to the team because we have musicians that come in with us and they're so gracious like they've spent a lot of money on their equipment their guitars are worth a lot like and they're just like yeah go for it you want to go have it and they allow these men to come and try things out some of them have got no idea how to play an instrument but they have a go anyway others are

23:15.330 --> 23:38.418
immensely talented and this is the only opportunity they get to play an instrument and to have that creativity and that freedom so it started from this place of like okay come on come and worship with us which then led to this a guy came up and started playing the keys and then they started worshiping and then a guy came up to me and was like Miss can I have the microphone and I'm thinking

23:38.754 --> 23:42.880
Always a dangerous day, even in church to be fair.

23:42.900 --> 23:43.601
Absolutely.

23:43.621 --> 23:44.682
This could go either way.

23:44.743 --> 23:48.608
And I wasn't sure how the officers were going to respond either because this is after the service.

23:48.628 --> 23:50.170
They're getting ready to go back to their cells.

23:50.791 --> 23:53.595
And I was like, OK, here you go.

23:53.835 --> 23:56.720
And he started wrapping and singing Waymaker.

23:57.240 --> 24:01.266
And the entire room started worshiping with him.

24:01.346 --> 24:05.236
Now, I can say that's one of the most exciting worship experiences that I've ever had.

24:05.276 --> 24:06.679
It's so cool.

24:08.103 --> 24:08.784
It's so cool.

24:09.326 --> 24:14.418
And now, because of that, we now invite a couple of the guys to

24:14.530 --> 24:17.713
play the guitar and to play the keys when we go in there.

24:17.733 --> 24:21.377
So we're worshipping together now, and it is beautiful.

24:21.697 --> 24:30.225
We've got guys who come to the Alpha course who are writing their own songs, writing their own raps, and at the end of Alpha, they're trying it out with some of the guys that play instruments.

24:30.626 --> 24:32.347
So it turns into this jamming session.

24:32.608 --> 24:34.209
He's like, Miss, Miss, what do you think of these words?

24:34.249 --> 24:35.410
Is this biblically accurate?

24:35.430 --> 24:36.912
And I'm like, I don't know, maybe.

24:37.292 --> 24:39.214
I hope so.

24:39.514 --> 24:40.055
It's great.

24:40.175 --> 24:41.536
It's really, really beautiful.

24:41.556 --> 24:43.378
We're just seeing signs of light

24:43.618 --> 24:48.666
life springing up all over the place and it is the biggest privilege.

24:48.766 --> 24:53.693
I can't tell you the buzz that we as a team get from being in that place.

24:54.074 --> 24:59.962
We get much more from them than they receive from ours and God is doing a new thing in that place.

25:00.022 --> 25:07.794
It's super, super exciting.

25:08.706 --> 25:10.228
I love this on so many levels.

25:10.348 --> 25:12.610
Firstly, because I think isn't that just the kingdom.

25:13.011 --> 25:27.846
We often take what we think we have into a place and of course you and the team are bringing light and hope and love and building those bridges that we spoke of earlier into Champs of Prism which is beautiful.

25:28.647 --> 25:34.994
But I love that this is the way God works that actually we are not only slightly enriched by that.

25:35.138 --> 25:42.791
even more blessed and even more enriched by what those people that we are there to serve bring to us and that's just the beauty of the kingdom for me.

25:44.093 --> 26:01.682
Two things I just want to pick up on briefly because you talked about that day when seven of the inmates in Alpha gave their lives to Jesus and there was something really profound for Peter and I that week because here at the gathering on the Sunday

26:01.890 --> 26:11.622
we invited people to respond to the gospel and we had seven responses here in church and then it was, what day was it, Tuesday?

26:11.722 --> 26:24.498
So the Tuesday of the same week, same number in Champs of Prison and for the two of us, we've talked for a really long time about the fact that we want to see this bridge built

26:24.610 --> 26:48.722
into our community so that actually what happens in a church is going out into our city, into our neighbourhoods, but also that there's this through flow in the other direction and this felt like such a significant moment and that kind of critical mass of what we have been longing for and praying for, that there was this symmetry between what happened here

26:48.930 --> 26:54.798
in the building and what was happening out there and obviously there's more that happens than we'll ever know.

26:54.818 --> 27:08.418
We can't always gauge what's happening but that to us was such an encouraging sign and we want you as a church to be encouraged by that and to keep praying for this because there's more to come for certain.

27:09.099 --> 27:17.170
But secondly, Eddie won't say this because she's probably got too much in her head to actually say to you all but

27:17.410 --> 27:22.257
The commitment to do alpha, we're not talking a small commitment.

27:22.718 --> 27:27.385
We run alpha in church and that's already a significant commitment for those on the team.

27:27.846 --> 27:31.852
But alpha in prison runs every single week of the year.

27:32.333 --> 27:34.737
So that is no small commitment.

27:34.797 --> 27:40.946
This is us being a consistent presence week on week.

27:41.026 --> 27:51.888
And I suppose I'm saying that because these guys need your prayers, but also there may be some of you that are just sitting here thinking, I could get involved with that.

27:52.089 --> 27:54.053
I feel like I could get on board with that.

27:54.514 --> 28:02.290
You know, if we're not spending our lives on the kingdom of God, if we're not spending our time advancing that,

28:02.914 --> 28:05.899
We're losing out, but also other people are losing out.

28:05.919 --> 28:09.886
So what could be on the other side of your committed yes today, I wonder?

28:10.226 --> 28:11.489
Just throwing that out there.

28:12.771 --> 28:15.636
Okay, so we need to move on from the prison reluctantly.

28:15.776 --> 28:17.378
I know you've got many more stories, actually.

28:17.399 --> 28:19.202
If we have time, maybe you'll give us one more.

28:19.863 --> 28:24.210
But for now, let's move on because I'd love us to talk about flourish.

28:24.354 --> 28:28.961
and the work that we're doing into secondary schools and into Champsford College.

28:29.081 --> 28:32.407
I believe we're now working into five local schools, is that right?

28:32.527 --> 28:33.809
Yeah, five local schools.

28:34.109 --> 28:42.002
And the reason why we don't do more than that is not because we don't want to, or they don't want us to, it's just purely a case of capacity.

28:42.783 --> 28:45.307
So the minute we can, we will be going further.

28:46.208 --> 28:47.410
But flourish has been

28:48.130 --> 28:50.922
going for about 15 years, which is amazing.

28:51.003 --> 28:52.148
I mean, just that in itself.

28:52.389 --> 28:58.034
The fact that we've been investing in the lives of young girls in our secondary schools for nearly 15 years is

28:58.498 --> 29:01.983
incredible and it continues to flourish.

29:02.003 --> 29:03.986
I mean, it's been rewritten many times.

29:04.046 --> 29:08.893
We look at it quite strategically every couple of years and go, okay, is this still relevant?

29:08.933 --> 29:10.375
Do we need to adapt this?

29:10.796 --> 29:15.283
What are they actually facing in the real world right now and adapt to that?

29:15.623 --> 29:18.107
But it's brilliant and it is continuing to flourish.

29:19.088 --> 29:22.994
There's so much about it that I just absolutely love.

29:23.426 --> 29:27.294
We work with around 250 girls a year during the course.

29:27.314 --> 29:36.011
It's a six-week course and it is all about building self-esteem, value and understanding their place in the world.

29:38.196 --> 29:45.330
It's a safe and inclusive place for girls, which there aren't that many of, particularly in the school environment.

29:46.178 --> 29:47.620
I didn't really love school.

29:47.840 --> 29:49.382
It wasn't my favorite place to be.

29:49.563 --> 29:52.547
In fact, I was there as little as possible, if I'm honest.

29:52.607 --> 29:54.990
I did the bare minimum to get to where I needed to be.

29:55.511 --> 29:57.073
And it wasn't fun.

29:57.614 --> 30:05.144
And part of the reason why it wasn't fun was because there was such an expectation on me as a girl to be a certain way.

30:05.305 --> 30:07.568
And I just felt very overwhelmed by it all.

30:07.628 --> 30:12.555
And had there been something like this, then who knows how my life might have looked?

30:13.916 --> 30:15.058
We look at things like,

30:15.554 --> 30:25.207
and perfectionism and body image and what the media tells us about who we are, how to use the power of our words to build people up rather than to tear them down.

30:25.728 --> 30:40.828
We look at consent and the power of our yes and no and that particularly has been really interesting recently because we've been putting together some grant funding and so we've got a lot of feedback from the schools which has been remarkable and really encouraging actually.

30:41.269 --> 30:45.234
And one of the things that we've noticed in doing the stats

30:45.378 --> 31:10.674
is that the biggest jump in terms of where they were when they started and where they were when they finished was their understanding of how important and how powerful their know can be and I just think if nothing else that is amazing just basic things like if you go to somebody's house and they offer you a drink are you going to say if you want to or not and the majority of them say oh I just wouldn't ask I just wouldn't say anything because

31:10.754 --> 31:13.000
They are not empowered to use their voices.

31:13.722 --> 31:15.106
So that's been really interesting.

31:15.146 --> 31:16.089
So interesting.

31:16.470 --> 31:17.392
The girls love it.

31:18.054 --> 31:20.621
It's very different from their normal school sessions.

31:20.982 --> 31:25.234
They love coming out for an hour and having real investment into who they are.

31:25.442 --> 31:28.366
We have the most incredible team.

31:28.566 --> 31:29.727
They're beautiful.

31:30.128 --> 31:42.803
And I think every single person on our team has wrestled with some of this stuff themselves, which means they're perfectly placed to feed into the lives of these girls from a place of understanding and knowing.

31:42.843 --> 31:48.350
And a lot of them say that they are healing whilst they're bringing healing to these girls.

31:48.430 --> 31:50.512
So it's not just about what they're bringing.

31:50.612 --> 31:55.378
They're actually receiving a huge amount from it as well.

31:57.186 --> 32:26.738
The schools have said that the girls are more engaged in their school life as a result of flourish, that they have better appear and student teacher relationships as a result of flourish, that they are not in isolation or in detention as regularly because of flourish, that they are able to coexist in their classrooms much more easily because of what we do and what we bring and that they are empowered to speak

32:26.946 --> 32:31.773
about what they want and what they don't want in their environments that they find themselves.

32:32.133 --> 32:34.957
And I just think that is brilliant.

32:35.138 --> 32:41.467
I mean, one of the reasons we do flourish is because we don't want them to end up needing restored.

32:42.208 --> 32:50.800
So young girls who have got low self esteem and low self value are far more likely to find themselves in abusive relationships as they get older.

32:51.261 --> 32:52.242
So if we can

32:52.386 --> 32:59.398
preempt that problem and deal with that issue and raise their self esteem and their self worth at that age in its year eight.

32:59.438 --> 33:12.059
So it's early in their secondary school career and maybe just maybe we might avoid some of those girls turning into women who are struggling to get out of an abusive relationship.

33:12.360 --> 33:13.442
So that's the reason.

33:13.462 --> 33:18.290
It just so happens that it's loads of fun and that the girls love it.

33:18.626 --> 33:26.637
We've got one story actually and it sounds like a bit of a negative story but it just shows the grace that our and facilitators have.

33:26.697 --> 33:33.366
So there was a particular group at one of the schools who had a couple of really tricky girls in the group.

33:33.427 --> 33:39.475
They were really disruptive and they found it very hard to connect and it was just difficult.

33:40.296 --> 33:44.562
And then they went away, they'd finished the session, they went away for the week and then

33:44.834 --> 33:54.043
They were told when they went back that these two girls had been removed from the group because of some of the things they were saying about the facilitators outside of the environment.

33:54.084 --> 33:56.506
And it was pretty dark and pretty awful.

33:57.307 --> 34:00.150
And I spoke to my facilitators, I was like, what do you need from us?

34:00.170 --> 34:01.351
Like, how can we support you?

34:01.371 --> 34:02.152
Blah, blah, blah, blah.

34:02.412 --> 34:03.693
How do you want this to go?

34:03.713 --> 34:05.675
And they were like, no, we're all good.

34:06.096 --> 34:08.919
And we want to give them the opportunity to come back if they want to.

34:09.339 --> 34:10.540
And I just thought, you know what?

34:10.600 --> 34:12.082
That is grace.

34:12.162 --> 34:14.906
That is so much grace poured out on these girls.

34:14.966 --> 34:18.651
These girls had said some really hurtful things about their facilitators.

34:19.112 --> 34:22.256
Yet they were like, no, I'm going to show the love of Jesus in this way.

34:22.316 --> 34:24.780
And I'm going to say it's okay for you to come back.

34:24.860 --> 34:28.725
Yeah, we need some boundaries put in place and that won't be tolerated again.

34:28.786 --> 34:38.940
But you get to come back into this environment despite your behavior because we see past that to you and we can see how much you need this.

34:39.341 --> 34:40.402
So I just love that.

34:40.738 --> 34:43.341
That is so beautiful, so beautiful.

34:43.422 --> 34:55.577
And I think having two daughters myself, one of the things I keep saying at the moment is I just don't feel as a parent that I can pour enough confidence into my girls.

34:55.597 --> 35:02.506
I just want to pour as much confidence into them now as they navigate school life and as they begin to grow.

35:02.707 --> 35:08.274
And I'm so thankful that something like Flourish exists here in our city because

35:08.514 --> 35:10.537
They don't just need to hear this from me.

35:10.597 --> 35:13.941
They need to hear it from as many voices as possible.

35:14.081 --> 35:30.223
And I'm so grateful that we as a church have an opportunity to give voice to some of this stuff, to open those dialogues and to talk about the power of our words, the power of our yes and our no, and what it looks like to build one another up, to have a healthy self-esteem.

35:30.423 --> 35:32.786
All of that is so, so necessary.

35:33.058 --> 35:41.486
Now, thinking about flourish, I know you've got big vision and you did a lead to the fact that we want to do something similar ultimately for boys.

35:41.506 --> 35:52.016
You've been in the process of developing a course that really matters to us as well, that we don't just focus on girls because that's only 50% of the story and the population.

35:53.498 --> 35:56.901
But we do have some very real constraints at the moment, don't we?

35:56.921 --> 36:02.226
And I'd just love to talk about, okay, what are some of our needs, but also what are some of our future hopes?

36:02.434 --> 36:03.476
so that we can be praying?

36:04.439 --> 36:18.030
Yes, so I would imagine quite a few of you saw the TV show Adolescence and having watched that and my own experience of the secondary school environment, I was like, we can't just leave this.

36:18.531 --> 36:21.458
We need to do something for boys and

36:21.506 --> 36:30.159
perspective, Peter Nicky and various other people who had a similar uprising, like this cannot be the story for our boys either.

36:30.920 --> 36:34.686
And so Kate and I have been writing the course in order to get into schools.

36:35.227 --> 36:39.633
But as you say, there are some constrictions that we are facing with this work.

36:40.655 --> 36:42.157
And funding is one of those things.

36:43.098 --> 36:50.930
So Flourish has always been externally funded and a lot of our money has come through the Council over the years.

36:51.234 --> 37:05.761
With everything that's changing with local councils at the moment, that funding is drying up quite considerably and we are finding ourselves needing to reach out into different ways in order to fundraise because we do not want the reason why this has to stop to be because of money.

37:05.822 --> 37:07.505
That can't be the reason.

37:07.825 --> 37:10.430
The only reason it stops is there's not a problem anymore.

37:10.450 --> 37:14.578
Until that happens, we keep going as far as I'm concerned.

37:15.106 --> 37:22.717
We're not worried because we know that God provides, but it is a very real current barrier that we have and we do want to expand it.

37:22.737 --> 37:27.244
We don't want to limit this to five schools and only girls.

37:27.545 --> 37:31.971
We want to be in every single secondary school in Oxford, boys and girls.

37:32.011 --> 37:39.763
That's going to take resource, that's going to take facilitators, that's going to take men stepping up as well in order to make that happen in schools.

37:40.123 --> 37:41.906
Yes, we can do it as women, but

37:42.050 --> 37:59.031
Wouldn't it be great if we had men delivering a course to boys about what it means to be a man and how you can develop that, that you don't have to follow this very narrow path that you're shown, that you can deviate from that and you can still be just as much of a man.

37:59.651 --> 38:04.657
So we're really passionate about that and we love more people to be praying.

38:04.718 --> 38:11.666
We have an incredible group of people who every second Wednesday

38:11.746 --> 38:13.428
pray for our community work.

38:14.049 --> 38:22.599
They go together on Zoom, they pray together, we kind of send in any prayer requests that we might have, but they just diligently and consistently pray for what we do.

38:23.180 --> 38:25.383
And we'd love more people to get involved in that.

38:25.423 --> 38:29.628
I know Rosemary would be like, yes, please, more than Mary are, please come and join us.

38:30.349 --> 38:33.112
So prayer is the undergirding for everything that we do.

38:33.132 --> 38:34.574
Without that, we are nothing.

38:35.135 --> 38:36.076
So prayer, yes.

38:36.537 --> 38:40.882
But we'll say, if you work for a business and they are

38:41.378 --> 38:45.922
in the business or getting tax relief by donating to local charities, then please.

38:46.523 --> 38:48.165
We've got some information that we can give you.

38:48.185 --> 38:49.226
You can hand that over.

38:49.846 --> 38:58.194
There's various, there's loads of creative ways that we can get money in order to continue this work because this is not where it ends.

38:58.294 --> 39:03.980
There is so much more that we can be investing into our local community in this way.

39:04.100 --> 39:05.381
It's so very needed.

39:05.882 --> 39:10.386
Every school in their feedback, well, like, if you could offer us more, we'd take it.

39:10.690 --> 39:14.036
We can't actually do our pastoral work without you.

39:14.056 --> 39:16.200
You feel a vital gap.

39:16.661 --> 39:18.103
So the need is there.

39:18.524 --> 39:19.846
We're answering that need.

39:19.866 --> 39:21.469
We just need more.

39:21.489 --> 39:23.793
So that's something for us to be praying for, Church.

39:23.954 --> 39:28.602
I mean, I really do believe that God wants to provide for this in all those ways.

39:28.642 --> 39:30.866
Perhaps you're sitting here today, you're a guy.

39:31.010 --> 39:36.118
and your heart is just beginning to pound a little bit faster because this is something you're passionate about.

39:36.518 --> 39:38.521
If that's you, come and find Eddie.

39:38.602 --> 39:43.809
I know all of us, we'd love to talk to you about how you could get involved in the future.

39:43.850 --> 39:48.997
Perhaps you're sitting here and you think, gosh, you know, I really want to be praying for this.

39:49.218 --> 39:54.826
I can't tell you how much your prayers and our prayers make a difference to those who are serving on the ground.

39:55.688 --> 39:59.954
Eddie is, we're giving the highlights today.

40:00.322 --> 40:06.327
But there is a lot of resistance when you are out there pioneering things in different spaces.

40:06.607 --> 40:09.550
And that requires a church who are praying.

40:09.950 --> 40:11.632
And this is something we're passionate about.

40:11.652 --> 40:12.873
We have a prayer room here.

40:13.313 --> 40:15.315
Come in and get praying for our community.

40:15.735 --> 40:17.016
Add yourself to the Zoom.

40:17.377 --> 40:18.818
Commit to praying daily.

40:18.878 --> 40:22.241
However you want to do that, we need your prayers.

40:22.421 --> 40:30.308
And finally, as she said, if you're somebody that maybe has access to pots of funding, or perhaps you're someone that's really

40:30.288 --> 40:33.311
really skilled in putting together fundraising bids.

40:33.771 --> 40:34.952
We would love your help.

40:35.273 --> 40:38.916
We can't be expert at everything here in Skylar Church.

40:38.936 --> 40:43.881
There is so much beyond this one area that takes place in and through the life of the Church.

40:43.961 --> 40:51.689
I could interview so many people on our team and our wider core team who volunteer about what they are currently doing.

40:52.189 --> 40:57.394
So if you have expertise that you could bring to you to Eddie and the team, we would

40:57.474 --> 40:58.816
absolutely love that.

40:58.937 --> 41:05.749
So please just take that as a way as a little how could I help be part of the solution for that.

41:06.190 --> 41:17.170
Now Eddie you talked about the fact that this is I suppose let's call it a proactive way of preparing girls for some of the issues that will face them

41:17.410 --> 41:35.666
later in life or actually not even later in life sadly now but some of the priorities for our local authorities and for the police in particular we're going to touch on now because one of the other things that we're significantly involved in is the Ministry of Restored and

41:35.746 --> 41:41.654
If you've been in the church for any length of time, you will remember that we went through whole church training on this.

41:41.714 --> 41:43.796
We had Becca Leg, he heads up restored.

41:44.297 --> 41:55.812
We stand against domestic violence and domestic abuse in all its forms, whether that is inside the church and Christian households and families and relationships or whether that is beyond.

41:56.433 --> 41:58.575
And the work has really grown.

41:58.615 --> 42:00.658
We were the first beacon church

42:00.834 --> 42:04.259
We're really proud in the right sense of the word of that.

42:04.419 --> 42:09.406
You know, that was a pioneering step and we've always had that pioneering DNA as a church.

42:10.007 --> 42:26.930
But I want to quote Chief Constable Ben Julian Harrington because I read this quote this week on the Essex Police Facebook page and it said this, violence against women and girls remains one of the most pressing issues of our time.

42:27.586 --> 42:37.405
When half of the population cannot feel safe, and I do want to also acknowledge that it happens to men as well, and we're very aware of that, and we are working into that too.

42:38.306 --> 42:46.642
But when half of the population cannot feel safe, whether in public or in their own homes, it becomes a national crisis.

42:47.010 --> 42:48.652
and we will not ignore it.

42:49.172 --> 42:52.796
Now, I was moved by that quote because I thought that's what we stand for.

42:53.056 --> 42:57.881
As a church, we will not ignore this either, whether that's in the church or beyond the church.

42:57.941 --> 43:00.123
We want to stand with victims.

43:00.143 --> 43:04.107
We want to stand with those who are living in that place of oppression.

43:04.147 --> 43:15.218
But I also noticed that Essex Police had to disable the comments on that quote because of so much negativity.

43:16.226 --> 43:17.007
That's horrific.

43:17.407 --> 43:18.508
I just feel like that's horrific.

43:18.528 --> 43:20.650
That is not okay.

43:21.471 --> 43:25.815
But it shows you that this is such a hard area to be working into.

43:26.336 --> 43:27.457
This is not easy.

43:27.477 --> 43:28.578
There's resistance.

43:29.138 --> 43:33.703
Now, I want to know how our work has been quietly expanding ever since Eddy.

43:33.823 --> 43:39.728
I know you probably won't be able to share specific stories for understandable reasons and we would not want you to.

43:40.149 --> 43:42.871
But can you give us a snapshot of the difference we're making?

43:42.891 --> 43:45.554
We're hitting time, but let's go for it.

43:46.114 --> 43:52.268
Yeah, I mean, it is the very nature of it means that it's secretly happening behind the scenes.

43:53.009 --> 44:00.626
So you might not necessarily hear us talking about what's going on, but it doesn't mean that nothing is going on and one in four.

44:00.706 --> 44:02.508
are affected by the domestic abuse.

44:02.588 --> 44:04.870
One in four women are affected by domestic abuse.

44:04.890 --> 44:06.071
That is the alarming stats.

44:06.091 --> 44:09.215
And that's the same in this room as anywhere else in the country.

44:09.255 --> 44:10.516
Don't get it twisted.

44:10.556 --> 44:11.597
This can happen here.

44:12.177 --> 44:16.642
One in six men, and the likelihood is it's much higher than that, but they just don't disclose as much.

44:16.902 --> 44:20.085
So this is a huge problem in our society.

44:20.966 --> 44:24.450
So it's a necessary thing for us to be doing.

44:25.130 --> 44:26.932
Yes, we work quietly.

44:27.373 --> 44:28.754
We offer safety.

44:28.962 --> 44:31.245
We offer a non-judgmental space.

44:31.505 --> 44:38.033
We offer understanding because many of us, many of the team, myself included, have a lived experience of this.

44:38.534 --> 44:46.844
So we are able to meet these women mostly, but some men as well, at a place of understanding, which is so very important.

44:48.627 --> 44:53.092
We work in with around 60 women, either within our church or the wider community.

44:53.673 --> 44:57.618
And just recently, over the last year, we've seen a real

44:58.146 --> 45:14.066
increase in other churches in the area, reaching out for advice and support and just a bit of guidance on how to deal with domestic abuse in their own context, which is great because sometimes we can be a bit funny about asking other people that are doing the same sort of stuff of us.

45:14.370 --> 45:15.252
for advice, can't we?

45:15.292 --> 45:16.936
We can be a bit like, well, no, I don't want to ask them.

45:16.996 --> 45:18.239
They might think we don't know anything.

45:18.620 --> 45:19.442
But there's none of that.

45:19.502 --> 45:21.006
There's just like the barriers have dropped.

45:21.026 --> 45:21.948
And it's just like, do you know what?

45:22.490 --> 45:23.372
You've had the training.

45:23.392 --> 45:24.535
You're already doing it.

45:24.595 --> 45:25.417
Can you help us?

45:25.437 --> 45:30.770
Which is a beautiful sign of kingdom and of working together.

45:31.471 --> 45:32.594
Which is brilliant.

45:32.834 --> 45:44.882
We've just had a new injection of team who've just trained up over the last couple of months that have got a burning passion for this work.

45:45.090 --> 45:48.736
As you can see, there's one of me and there's a huge amount of stuff to do.

45:48.776 --> 45:53.503
And restored is one of those things that I'd love to do more, but I just don't have capacity.

45:53.543 --> 46:01.515
So this uprising of team who are just ready to go and have got loads of cool ideas is going to take this to the next level.

46:01.575 --> 46:02.997
So we're really excited about that.

46:03.859 --> 46:04.780
So exciting.

46:04.820 --> 46:06.002
Eddie, I mean,

46:06.082 --> 46:13.473
I could talk to you all day and there's a lot more that we wanted to chat through today that we haven't managed to get to but I'm really mindful of kids' church.

46:13.874 --> 46:15.256
More is really mindful of kids' church.

46:15.276 --> 46:26.694
Those guys are amazing up there but we don't want to overstep their boundaries because it's sometimes challenging looking after everybody else's children whilst we talk nicely and quietly down here.

46:26.754 --> 46:29.618
So I'm going to draw this to a close.

46:29.794 --> 46:46.002
I know that one of the other things had we had time that you wanted to touch on is our passion to do more into the area of mental health and we're passionate about kintsugi as one of the vehicles for that and we need people who are passionate about running kintsugi so if you're sitting here today and that's you

46:46.146 --> 47:01.170
please come and talk to Eddy, or if you know someone who's not here today and you've had this kind of conversation, training is available, but we really do need more man and woman power on the ground for mental health and kinsugi in particular, don't we?

47:01.350 --> 47:06.218
I think what it would be great for us to do is pray, and I'd love us to stand as a church as we do that.

47:06.719 --> 47:07.721
Eddy, come and stand here.

47:08.081 --> 47:13.650
First, I want to say thank you to all of the volunteers and team who serve.

47:14.018 --> 47:15.600
our vision for community.

47:15.640 --> 47:17.143
We're so grateful to you.

47:23.171 --> 47:35.630
And now I'd love to pray, and I'm praying over Eddie more as a kind of a symbol because she's spearheading this, but obviously really what we're praying for is just the extension of kingdom calm and those verses in Isaiah.

47:35.650 --> 47:37.633
So why don't you stretch your hands out with me.

47:39.255 --> 47:43.922
Lord, I thank you so much for all that we've heard today.

47:44.386 --> 48:00.210
And Lord, I realise that behind some of those conversations and those moments where we could have lingered, there would have been countless more people, stories, impact, challenge than we could ever convey in this short space of time.

48:01.072 --> 48:07.361
But Father, we realise that right now the harvest is ripe and the labourers are few.

48:08.142 --> 48:10.546
And Lord, we just asked today

48:10.914 --> 48:21.853
that you would provide absolutely everything that we need to continue the work that we're doing and not only maintain it but to expand it further.

48:22.253 --> 48:27.262
Lord, to dream bigger, to step out into new and uncharted waters.

48:27.663 --> 48:31.890
Father, I pray today that for those who have their arm out and

48:31.938 --> 48:37.587
maybe a real desire to get involved, that they wouldn't walk away and forget about it.

48:38.007 --> 48:52.850
Lord, for those who could maybe open doors for us into funding pots or into income streams to help us fund some of the areas where we really need to see finance coming in, I just asked Lord that you would do what only you can.

48:53.250 --> 49:11.801
And for those who feel called to pray, to be those prayer warriors who would surround this work with protection, but also pray for those new and pioneering inroads that we will make, just like Marwai Brown, when she looked out of her doorstep and knew she could meet a need.

49:12.182 --> 49:17.170
Father, I pray that we would always be a church that sees the need

49:17.250 --> 49:23.886
that knows that we can't do it in our own strength and in our natural resource, but still takes a face step to do it anyway.

49:24.307 --> 49:27.654
And I pray a blessing over Eddie and all of the team today.

49:28.095 --> 49:30.501
We thank you for each and everyone.

49:30.561 --> 49:32.546
May they go from strength to strength.

49:33.448 --> 49:34.290
Amen.

